{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17496742","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17496742"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T08:55:26+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T08:55:26+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1412"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1412","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1412"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.58,0.03,0.04,0.06,0.29]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1412"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109453"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1412","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1412"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1412"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91818"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"13"},{"type":"tags","id":"15"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"160"},{"type":"tags","id":"377"},{"type":"tags","id":"489"},{"type":"tags","id":"1036"},{"type":"tags","id":"1911"},{"type":"tags","id":"2074"},{"type":"tags","id":"2282"},{"type":"tags","id":"2602"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4982"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"8118"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"},{"type":"tags","id":"12911"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"880"},{"type":"contributions","id":"998"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3856"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12292"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39189"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40873"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42310"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43080"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44770"},{"type":"contributions","id":"46351"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109453","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/109453"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 76-year-old woman, who has a 42 pack-year smoking history, presents to the Emergency Department with shortness of breath that has progressively become worse over the past two days. She does not have a cough, haemoptysis or any chest pain associated with her dyspnoea. She has no recent travel history. Her past medical history includes stage IV breast cancer, for which she is on palliative chemotherapy, and chronic kidney disease with an eGFR of 46 mL/minute/1.73 m\u003Csup\u003E2\u003C/sup\u003E. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, her blood pressure is 134/90 mmHg, pulse 110/min and regular, temperature 36.9\u00b0C, and oxygen saturation 94% on room air. There is some erythema of her right lower leg, which is tender on palpation. She has bronchovesicular breath sounds and no adventitious sounds on auscultation of the lungs. Her ECG is below (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate diagnostic investigation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["CT pulmonary angiogram","Chest X-ray","D-dimer","Transthoracic echocardiography","Ventilation/perfusion (V/Q) scan"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe most likely aetiology for the patient\u0027s dyspnoea is pulmonary embolism (PE). This is supported by the patient\u0027s older age, active malignancy and treatment with chemotherapy, all of which place the patient at a higher risk of pulmonary embolism. Most importantly, the presence of tender, unilateral leg erythema is strongly suspicious for a deep vein thrombosis (DVT), which is the most likely cause for her PE. To take a quantified approach, applying the \u003Ca href=\u0022https://www.mdcalc.com/wells-criteria-pulmonary-embolism\u0022\u003EWells\u0027 Criteria for Pulmonary Embolism\u003C/a\u003E, the patient scores 8.5, putting her at \u003Cstrong\u003Ehigh clinical probability of a pulmonary embolism\u003C/strong\u003E. Her ECG demonstrates sinus tachycardia - the most common ECG pattern in PE, but of course wholly non-specific. (There is also a potentially evolving \u003Ca href=\u0022https://litfl.com/ecg-changes-in-pulmonary-embolism/\u0022\u003ES1Q3T3 pattern\u003C/a\u003E, which is famously associated with but actually relatively weakly predictive of PE.)\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDespite traditional teaching of a \u0027classic triad\u0027 of symptoms, chest pain and haemoptysis are not necessarily present in the setting of PE, and are absolutely not required for diagnosis. Overall, the most common symptom of PE is unexplained dyspnoea. Due to its non-specific symptoms and signs, PE has been called the \u0027great masquerader\u0027.  It is important to be aware of the risk of PE with chronic kidney disease given the increased hypercoagulative state of CKD from increased fibrinogen, von Willibrand factor, VIIa and XIIa and decrease in plasminogen activator inhibitor - 1.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECT pulmonary angiography (CTPA)\u003C/strong\u003E is the gold standard for diagnosis of PE, capable of visualising emboli down to sixth-generation branches of the vascular tree. Although this patient has chronic kidney disease with an eGFR of 46 mL/min/1.73 m\u003Csup\u003E2\u003C/sup\u003E, the risk of contrast-induced nephropathy is low and can be further reduced with pre-hydration. In practice, alternatives to CTPA tend to be considered with eGFR below 30 mL/min/1.73 m\u003Csup\u003E2\u003C/sup\u003E, however this is still a relative contraindication.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVentilation/perfusion (V/Q) scans\u003C/strong\u003E are considered second-line, and are typically employed when a contraindication exists to the relatively high radiation dose of a CTPA - most commonly, pregnancy or in young patients. V/Q scans have a sensitivity of 77.4% and a specificity of 97.7% when compared to CTPA or digital subtraction angiography and are less reliable.  Most scans return indeterminate results, less than half of patients with otherwise-confirmed PEs return a \u0027high probability\u0027 scan, and up to 40% of such patients return a \u0027low probability\u0027 scan.  Additionally, V/Q scans are less affected by renal impairment as they do not require contrast agents, making them a consideration in patients with severe renal dysfunction or risk of contrast induced nephropathy.  \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ED-dimer\u003C/strong\u003E is used in the setting of a low clinical suspicion of DVT/PE as a \u0027rule out\u0027 test; it has \u0026gt;95% sensitivity for PE but is very non-specific, also rising in patients with cancer, sepsis, myocardial infarct, pregnancy, post-operatively, and more. Most \u003Cstrong\u003Echest x-rays\u003C/strong\u003E in PE are normal, as are most \u003Cstrong\u003Etransthoracic echocardiograms\u003C/strong\u003E, and although both can be useful for excluding differential diagnoses they are not the most appropriate choice with a high clinical suspicion of PE.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["CT pulmonary angiography is the gold standard for diagnosis of PE.","V/Q scans are second-line investigations, typically used where radiation exposure is contraindicated (e.g. young or pregnant)."],"references":["Kruger PC, Eikelboom JW, Douketis JD, Hankey GJ. Pulmonary embolism: update on diagnosis and management. Med J Aust. 2019 Jul;211(2):82-87. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/31216072/","Hepburn-Brown M, Darvall J, Hammerschlag G. Acute pulmonary embolism: a concise review of diagnosis and management. Intern Med J. 2019 Jan;49(1):15-27. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/30324770/","Lawrence N, Vadera S, Atkinson H, et al. V/Q scan. In: Radiopaedia.org [online]. Accessed 2024 Jun 17. Available at: https://doi.org/10.53347/rID-46829","Kumar G, Sakhuja A, Taneja A, Majumdar T, Patel J, Whittle J, Nanchal R; Milwaukee Initiative in Critical Care Outcomes Research (MICCOR) Group of Investigators. Pulmonary embolism in patients with CKD and ESRD. Clinical Journal of the American Society of Nephrology. 2012 Oct;7(10):1584-90. doi: 10.2215/CJN.00250112."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91818"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1412"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"10436"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"10436","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/10436"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/8d4b81a6-8eef-4f64-ab68-fbb1bbc735ae.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/8d4b81a6-8eef-4f64-ab68-fbb1bbc735ae.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":1433,"height":627}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91818","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/91818"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-21T15:57:39+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-05T09:16:49+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1412"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109453"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","li